  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is generally considered a felony offense in most jurisdictions, including the United States, and is punishable by severe penalties. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally obtained money (from activities such as drug trafficking, fraud, or corruption) appear legitimate by passing it through a complex sequence of financial transactions.\n\nIn the U.S., the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act (MLCA)** criminalize money laundering activities. Penalties for money laundering can include:\n\n- Substantial fines (ranging from hundreds of thousands to millions of dollars, depending on the amount involved)\n- Imprisonment (often up to 20 years per count, and sometimes more for aggravated cases)\n- Forfeiture of assets related to the laundering scheme\n\nThe severity of the penalties depends on factors such as the amount of money laundered, the underlying criminal activity, and whether the individual is a repeat offender. International cooperation through organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** also ensures that money laundering is prosecuted globally.\n\nIf you have specific concerns or legal questions about money laundering, it\u2019s advisable to consult a qualified attorney.",
